# Component Breakdown

## utils.py (Base62 Encoder)
Instead of using long random hashes, the system uses database auto-increment IDs (1, 2, 3, ...). These IDs are converted into Base62 format using the characters:

- 0–9  
- a–z  
- A–Z  

This approach ensures:
- Short and compact URLs  
- No collisions or duplication  
- Efficient and predictable encoding  

---

## main.py (Routing)

### POST /api/shorten
- Accepts a long URL  
- Stores it in the database  
- Generates a short code  
- Returns the shortened URL  

### GET /{short_code}
- Retrieves the original URL from the database  
- Logs click data asynchronously  
- Redirects the user to the original URL  

### GET /api/analytics/{short_code}
- Returns all analytics data associated with the given short code  

---

# How the Analytics Identification Works

When a user clicks a short link (e.g., `http://localhost:8000/aB3`), an HTTP request is sent to the FastAPI backend.

Before redirecting the user, the backend extracts important metadata from the request:

## IP Address (`request.client.host`)
- Identifies the network origin of the request  
- Useful for tracking user location (basic level)  

## User-Agent (`request.headers.get("user-agent")`)
- Automatically sent by the user's browser  
- Contains details about:
  - Operating System (Windows, Mac, iOS, etc.)  
  - Browser (Chrome, Safari, Edge, etc.)  

Example:
```
Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36...
```

## Timestamp (`datetime.utcnow()`)
- Records the exact server time when the click occurred  

---

### Data Storage
All this data is stored in the **SQLite database (clicks table)** and later used by the Streamlit dashboard.

The dashboard groups this data (mainly by date) to generate the **"Clicks Over Time"** visualization.

